<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="83" type="habitat">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="83">Habitat.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="83">
At the southern edge of the Sierra Madre Occidental Range in the Sierra 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Fría">Fria</normalizedToken>
de Aguascalientes, we recently found 
<taxonomicName class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Muhlenbergia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Muhlenbergia spatha" order="Rosales" pageId="0" pageNumber="83" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="spatha">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="83">Muhlenbergia spatha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in two localities south of the city of Zacatecas in a corridor located east of Villanueva: 1) 17.4 km east of Villanueva on flat table rock just above Arroyo &quot;El Muerto&quot; in open areas and 2) about 1 km northeast of the small village Palomas Viejas along Arroyo Juan Manuel on natural grasslands near cultivated fields. These two sites are approximately 204 km W (air distance) from the type locality southwest of San Luis 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Potosí">Potosi</normalizedToken>
in the Sierra de San Miguelito along the 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Río">Rio</normalizedToken>
Potosino (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.5642/aliso.20012001.08" author="Columbus, JT" journalOrPublisher="Aliso" pageId="0" pageNumber="83" pagination="45 - 90" refId="B4" refString="Columbus, JT, Bell, HL, Cerros-Tlatilpa, R, Griffith, MP, Porter, JM, 2001. Schaffnerella rediscovered! (Gramineae, Chloridoideae). Aliso 20: 45 - 90, DOI: https://doi.org/10.5642/aliso.20012001.08" title="Schaffnerella rediscovered! (Gramineae, Chloridoideae)." url="https://doi.org/10.5642/aliso.20012001.08" volume="20" year="2001">Columbus et al. 2001</bibRefCitation>
). According to Instituto Nacional de 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Estadística">Estadistica</normalizedToken>
, 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Geografía">Geografia</normalizedToken>
e 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Informática">Informatica</normalizedToken>
[INEGI] (2003, 2005), the Sierra San Miguelito is placed in the Mesa del Centro Province in the Sierra Madre Oriental. Near Villanueva, Zacatecas, the soils are Haplic Phaeozem (forming sodium carbonate, Na2CO3) over extrusive igneous rock (acidic) in a semi-dry climate with an annual mean temperature of 16°C and an annual mean precipitation of 60 cm (
<bibRefCitation author="INEGI" journalOrPublisher="Consejo Nacional de Ciencia Y Tecnologia, Mexico D. F." pageId="0" pageNumber="83" publicationUrl="http://www.inegi.org.mx/" refId="B9" refString="INEGI, 2008a. Cartas climatologicas. Conjunto de datos vectoriales. Escala 1:1 000000. http://www.inegi.org.mx/" title="Cartas climatologicas. Conjunto de datos vectoriales. Escala 1: 1 000000." url="http://www.inegi.org.mx/" year="2008 a">INEGI 2008a</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="INEGI" journalOrPublisher="Consejo Nacional de Ciencia Y Tecnologia, Mexico D. F." pageId="0" pageNumber="83" publicationUrl="http://www.inegi.org.mx/" refId="B10" refString="INEGI, 2008b. Perfiles de Suelos, Estados Unidos Mexicanos. Conjunto de datos vectoriales. Escala 1:1000000. http://www.inegi.org.mx/" title="Perfiles de Suelos, Estados Unidos Mexicanos. Conjunto de datos vectoriales. Escala 1: 1000000." url="http://www.inegi.org.mx/" year="2008 b">2008b</bibRefCitation>
). In the Sierra de San Miguelito along the Rio Potosino, the soils are Calcic Regosol (forming calcium carbonate, CaCO3) of medium texture over extrusive igneous rock (acidic) in a semi-dry climate with an annual mean temperature of 16 °C and an annual mean precipitation of 40 cm (
<bibRefCitation author="INEGI" journalOrPublisher="Consejo Nacional de Ciencia Y Tecnologia, Mexico D. F." pageId="0" pageNumber="83" publicationUrl="http://www.inegi.org.mx/" refId="B9" refString="INEGI, 2008a. Cartas climatologicas. Conjunto de datos vectoriales. Escala 1:1 000000. http://www.inegi.org.mx/" title="Cartas climatologicas. Conjunto de datos vectoriales. Escala 1: 1 000000." url="http://www.inegi.org.mx/" year="2008 a">INEGI 2008a</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="INEGI" journalOrPublisher="Consejo Nacional de Ciencia Y Tecnologia, Mexico D. F." pageId="0" pageNumber="83" publicationUrl="http://www.inegi.org.mx/" refId="B10" refString="INEGI, 2008b. Perfiles de Suelos, Estados Unidos Mexicanos. Conjunto de datos vectoriales. Escala 1:1000000. http://www.inegi.org.mx/" title="Perfiles de Suelos, Estados Unidos Mexicanos. Conjunto de datos vectoriales. Escala 1: 1000000." url="http://www.inegi.org.mx/" year="2008 b">2008b</bibRefCitation>
). Without field verification, it is uncertain whether the soil differences among these sites are significant, but we are reasonably certain that all are alkaline with an elevated pH.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="83" type="conservation status">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="83">Conservation status.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="83">The species is rare in Mexico and is known from only three recent collections. Since it is a diminutive, short-lived annual, the species is easily overlooked and the main concern seems to be loss of habitat via human impact, i.e. agriculture, dam and road construction.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
